shire, England","Caux, Allier, Auvergne, France":"Caux, Allier, Auvergne, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Pace","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from a vernacular short form of the Latin personal name <i>Paschalis</i> (see   Paschal  ).","English: nickname for a mild-mannered and peaceable person, from Middle English <i>pais</i>, <i>pace</i>, <i>pes(e)</i>, <i>pece</i> ‘peace, concord, amity’ (a borrowing of Old French <i>pais</i>, from Latin <i>pax</i>), or perhaps from the derived adjective <i>pes</i> ‘quiet, silent, peaceful’.","Italian: from the medieval personal name <i>Pace</i>, from the vocabulary word <i>pace</i> ‘peace’ (see 2 above), used for both males and females. In some instances it may represent a short form of the medieval personal name <i>Bonapace</i>, an omen or well-wishing name based on the same word."],"variants":[{"name":"Pacino","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Salvatore, Angelo, Franco, Vincenzo.","Italian: from the personal name <i>Pacino</i>, a pet form of   Pace  ."]},{"name":"Paci","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Salvatore, Domenic, Aldo, Arduino, Attilio, Dino, Domenico, Elisabetta, Enrico, Gino, Lamberto, Luigi, Mario, Sante.","Italian: patronymic or plural form of   Pace  .","Hungarian: habitational name for someone from a place called Pac in Bihar County."]},{"name":"Pacione","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Primo, Mario, Vito, Antonio, Carlo, Emilio, Enrico, Ernesto, Fernando, Franco, Guido, Luigi, Salvatore, Stefano.","Italian: nickname for a calm or peaceable person, from the vocabulary word <i>pacione</i>, or from the personal name   Pace   + the augmentative suffix <i>-one</i>."]},{"name":"Makepeace","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English <i>make</i> (Old English <i>macian</i>) + <i>peis</i>, <i>pes</i> ‘make peace’, probably for a professional arbitrator or for someone known for his skill at patching up quarrels, although it may also have been used ironically (see   Pace  )."]},{"name":"Pacella","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Antonio, Salvatore, Luciano, Nunzio, Querino, Rinaldo, Rocco, Dante, Donato, Giovanni, Guerino.","Italian: from a female pet form of the personal name <i>Pace</i> (see   Pace   3)."]},{"name":"Pacillo","meanings":["Italian (southern): from <i>Pacillo</i>, a pet form of the personal name   Pace  ."]},{"name":"Pacitto","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Domenic, Angelo, Antonio, Pasquale, Salvatore.","Italian: from a pet form of the personal name   Pace  ."]},{"name":"Paschal","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Pascal</i>, derived from Old French <i>Pasquale</i> and ultimately from Latin <i>Paschalis</i> ‘pertaining to Easter’ (from <i>pascha</i> ‘Easter’, via Greek and Aramaic from Hebrew <i>pesah</i> ‘Passover’). This was popular as a personal name throughout Christian Europe in the Middle Ages, mainly in honor of the festival of Christ's crucifixion and resurrection, often signifying someone born at Easter, but also in honor of a 9th-century pope and saint who bore the name.","French: variant of   Pascal   (a cognate of 1) and, in North America, (also) an altered form of this.","American shortened form of Greek <b>Paschalis</b>, which is of the same ultimate origin as 1 above, or of its patronymics and other derivatives, e.g. <b>Paschalakis</b>, <b>Paschalides</b>, <b>Paschalidis</b>, and <b>Paschaloudis</b>. Compare   Pascal  ."]},{"name":"Pacelli","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Rocco, Nicola, Angelo, Dominico, Franco, Giovanni, Guido, Luca, Luigi, Remo, Romeo, Salvatore.","Italian: patronymic or plural form of <i>Pacello</i>, a pet form of the personal name <i>Pace</i> (see   Pace   3)."]},{"name":"Pacetti","meanings":["Italian: patronymic or plural form of <b>Pacetto</b>, a pet form of the personal name <i>Pace</i> (see   Pace   3)."]}]},{"name":"Payes","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Spanish (<b>Payés</b>): nickname from <i>payés</i> ‘peasant farmer’, from Catalan <i>pagés</i>. This surname is most common in Guatemala and El Salvador."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Isabella","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , which has been popular in England since the 18th century and has recently become the preferred form of the name."],"variants":[{"name":"Isobella","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705181,"age":11,"year":"1035","julianDay":2099086,"title":"England Divided","description":"King Canute died in 1035 and England was divided between his three sons. His son Sweyn received Norway, Harthacanute received Denmark, and Harold Harefoot received North England.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705182,"age":42,"year":"1066","julianDay":2110409,"title":"Battle of Hastings","description":"Battle of Hastings was fought between the Norman-French army and the battle-wary English army on October 14, 1066. Duke William of Normandy believed he was the rightful king rather than Harold, who had been crowned king several months earlier. Harold was killed in battle and William was crowned king on Christmas Day 1066.","url":"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/learn/1066-and-the-norman-conquest/what-happened-battle-hastings/","urlTitle":"English Heritage - Battle of Hastings","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Isabella de Pace Payes was born in 1024, in Hauts-de-France, France, her father, Adam de Pays, was 25 and her mother, Herlève Herleva Harlette Arlette Arlotta, was 21. She had at least 1 daughter with Talsey d'Alcester. She died in 1085, in Shropshire, England, at the age of 61."},"et":{"1024–1085":"1024–1085","1030–Male":"1030–Surnud","1056–1131":"1056–1131","1000–1037":"1000–1037","1003–Female":"1003–Surnud","1037":"1037","1003":"1003","1024":"1024","1035":"1035","1056":"1056","1066":"1066","1000":"1000","1131":"1131","about 1037":"umbes 1037","1085":"1085","1030":"1030","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","Hauts-de-France, France":"Hauts-de-France, Prantsusmaa","Alcester, Warwickshire, England":"Alcester, Warwickshire, England","Caux, Allier, Auvergne, France":"Caux, Allier, Auvergne, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1024–1085":"1024–1085","1030–Male":"1030–Kuollut","1056–1131":"1056–1131","1000–1037":"1000–1037","1003–Female":"1003–Kuollut","1037":"1037","1003":"1003","1024":"1024","1035":"1035","1056":"1056","1066":"1066","1000":"1000","1131":"1131","about 1037":"noin 1037","1085":"1085","1030":"1030","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, Engl